<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="20" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 825.20/21A.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 15.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-14">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that the
                            following joint resolution, previously passed by the Senate, was passed
                            on the 6th <pb facs="0161" n="45" xml:id="pg_45"/> instant by the House
                            of Representatives and was signed by the President on May 11, 1912:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Resolved, etc.</hi>, That Capt. John W.
                                    Gulick, Coast Artillery Corps, United States Army, be, and he is
                                    hereby, permitted to accept from the Government of the Republic
                                    of Chile the position of instructor of the Coast Artillery of
                                    the Chilean Army and the emoluments, rights and privileges
                                    pertaining thereto.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>This information has already been telegraphed to the American Legation at
                            Santiago.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>